	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sun Sep 30, 2012 9:24 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Seeding the RNG</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yes, it's possible to choose a random element from a list of pointers into Huffman encoded data. But practically, to choose one at random, you're going to need a random seed with at least 13 bits of <a href="http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_(computing)" class="postlink">entropy</a>. You can't get much of a seed from key press timing; each press yields only about four quality bits. (The upper bits are predictable and therefore don't count as entropy.) I think that's why Rare's version requires the players to enter their names on an on-screen keyboard before the puzzle appears on Vanna's board.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
